        <h1>香港的銀行卡<br>
            專業術語
        </h1>
        <p>
            以下是關於信用卡的一些技術上和財務上的專業術語。如果你在尋找關於信用卡申請和信用卡利率的更深入的資料，你可以轉到我們的<a href="{baseUrlWithLang()}credit-card/guide">信用卡指南</a>或<a href="{baseUrlWithLang()}credit-card/faqs">常見問題</a>頁面
        </p>
        <div id="accordion">
            <h3>3D安全認證</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    This is an added layer of security that protects you from credit card fraud. Merchants using 3D secure would require an additional online authentication step everytime you make an online credit card or debit card transaction.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>年费</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Sometimes also referred to as membership fee, this is the cost charged by credit card issuers for maintaining credit card accounts.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>年利率（APR）</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Also referred to as the annual interest rate, the annual percentage rate is the yearly interest you pay on outstanding credit card balance.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>授權碼</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    This is the code issued by the credit card provider telling merchants that your card is valid and you have funds to cover the transaction at the time when authorisation is sought.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>未結餘額轉移</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    This is the process of to transferring outstanding credit card balance to another credit account that will allow you to settle outstanding balance by installments within a specified period, at a lower interest amount. Balance transfers are usually applied to high-interest credit cards, personal loans, revolving loans, overdraft accounts, etc.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>信用卡提現</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    This feature is made available by most credit card issuers, wherein the cardholder is allowed to withdraw cash over the counter or via ATMs. The amount you withdraw is deducted from your credit limit or funds on deposits. Cash advances are subject to a certain limit.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>無卡交易</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    A type of transaction wherein the cardholder is unable to physically supply the card to a merchant such as with over-the-phone, online, or mail order transactions. In such cases, bank authorisation would be sought by the merchant.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>支付網絡</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Card payment network providers including Visa, MasterCard, American Express, and UnionPay provide payment facilities that enable credit card issuers and banks establish financial partnershps with merchant establishments. Payment network providers charge banks and credit card issuers a fee for their services, with the exception of American Express which issues its own cards.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>現金回贈</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    A feature available to cardholders that enable them to get cash, on top of their purchase, with a debit card transaction using their credit card. Cashbacks are also subject to a limit.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>信用記錄</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    This is the record of payments you have made and loans you took in the past. Credit card issuers would look at this data as a basis in determining how much of a risk they are taking in lending you money.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>信貸限額/信用額度</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Refers to the maximum amount you may charge on your credit card. Your card may be declined or you can be imposed a penalty if you exceed your credit card limit. Over time, you may arrange to have your credit limit increase or decrease your credit limit.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>信用評分</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    A <a href="http://www.transunion.hk/personal/creditlearningcentre/creditscores_en.html" target="_blank">credit score</a> is an indicator of risk based on statistical validation as determined by credit providers and credit bureaus. It represents the entirety of your credit history in one numeric measure. Credit scores are subject to change depending on the latest information in your credit profile.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>雙幣信用卡</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Some banks in Hong Kong issue dual currency credit cards, which may settle transactions in RMB (for mainland China) and HKD (in Hong Kong and overseas). This feature is beneficial to cardholders who frequently travel in that it helps them save on foreign exchange fees.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>財務費用</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    These include the fees you pay to the lender for using borrowed money. Interest may be charged as a percentage of your outstanding balance. Interest rates vary for different credit cards.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>分期付款</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Installment plan is a feature available to some credit cards, wherein banks would settle a purchase in full and the cardholder would pay back the bank the full amount in installments.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>免息期</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Also called the grace period, this is the period of time, preceding the monthly due date (indicated in your credit card statement) during which no interest will be charged by the bank. After said period, credit card holder would have to pay interest on top of the amount due. The length of interest-free period varies from 20-59 days.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>優惠期</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    During the introductory period, banks may apply introductory interest rates to outstanding balances on your credit account.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>商戶</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Any business establishment where you purchase products or services.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>最低還款額</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    This is the portion of your outstanding credit card balance that you are required to pay, with the rest of the unpaid amount being subject to interest. Interest-free periods do not usually apply when you only make a minimum payment.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>網上銀行</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Refers to all electronic systems that enable you to access a host of banking services using the internet with a personal computer or mobile devices.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>密碼</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Personal identification numbe or PIN is the code that allows you to perform banking transactions, including cash advance withdrawals on your credit card, through ATMs. You can also make purchases without signing sales receipts using your PIN. PIN codes should not be shared to anyone.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>獎勵計劃</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    Most credit cards in Hong Kong offer a rewards program that enables card holders to earn points, air mileages, or cash rebates for credit card usage. Some issuers will charge you a fee to participate in the rewards program, particulary those that allow you to transfer points to frequent flyers programs. 
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>擔保卡</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    This is a type of credit card that requires the cardholder to make a security deposit before being granted a credit line. Secured cards are recommended if you have little or no credit history. Over time, if you are always prompt on monthly payments, you may arrange with your bank to switch to an unsecured card.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>驗證碼</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    This is the four-digit code which follows right after your card number, usually printed on the signature strip at the back of your card.
                </p>
            </div>
            <h3>環聯</h3>
            <div>
                <p>
                    環聯是一家國際認可的信用監控機構，他們從不同的途徑收集信息並向香港的銀行提供信用報告。你的信用報告將包括你的支付記錄、當前的信貸使用和申請資料。環聯並不參與批准或者拒絕信用卡申請的過程。
                </p>
            </div>
